m Methodism's Wesleyan beginnings to the prominence of women in local societies, the construction of African Methodism, the diverse social profile of Methodist men, and contests over the movement's future, Andrews charts Methodism's metamorphosis from a British missionary organization to a fully Americanized church. Weaving together narrative and analysis, Andrews explains Methodism's extraordinary popular appeal in rich and compelling new detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082359840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400823598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400823598.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK